  "prompt": "Is it true that everyone has to have chickenpox at least once in their lifetime?",
  "response": "No, it is not true that everyone has to have chickenpox at least once in their lifetime. While chickenpox, caused by the varicella-zoster virus, was once a common childhood illness, the widespread use of the varicella vaccine has significantly reduced the incidence of chickenpox. People who receive the vaccine are protected from getting the disease, and even if they do contract the virus after vaccination, the symptoms are usually much milder. Moreover, some individuals may have natural immunity due to asymptomatic infections or other factors. Therefore, not everyone will experience chickenpox in their lifetime.",
